<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n50083b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n50" href="#n50083b">N50 (VI.B.37)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n50all.htm#n50083b"> 83(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Dannebrog <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n50083b"><li>FW 323.09 </li><li><a href="../../flex/ma/lexma.htm#n50083b">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/ma/l39ma.htm#n50083b">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n50083b">MS BL 47479-61v</ms> </li><li>JJA 54:122 <a name="mad2" href="../../FF/fdra/mda.htm#mad2">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/ma/mad2.htm#n50083b">Draft: II.3&sect;1.2</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">In the ninth, tenth, and eleventh centuries the raven, the <mark>Danebrog</mark> of heathenism, waved victoriously in the western lands. It was with Canute the Great at Ashingdon, with the Norman William at Hastings, and was thus present at two conquests of England.<font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> If we may not assume that the present &ldquo;Danebrog,&rdquo; with its white, cross on a red ground, became the Danish national flag immediately after the introduction of Christianity, it is at least certain that the Danish kings, in the first two centuries after that event, bore flags with crosses as their personal banners, or marks; and particularly in the twelfth century, when the crusades against the heathen Wends began. <small> J.J.A. Worsaae, <a name="JJAW2" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#JJAW2"><cite title="source">An Account of the Danes and Norwegians in England, Scotland and Ireland</cite></a> (1852) 62-3</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Dannebrog (Danes&apos; Cloth: Danish flag, a red banner with a white cross on it). Miraculously descended from Heaven to save the valourous Valdemar II. at Lyndantse (the modern Reval). Donnybrook, Dublin. </mm> </dd></dl>
